VI want to talk to you today a little bit
p4
aVabout predictable irrationality.
p5
aVAnd my interest in irrational behavior
p6
aVstarted many years ago in the hospital.
p7
aVI was burned very badly.
p8
aVAnd if you spend a lot of time in hospital,
p9
aVyou'll see a lot of types of irrationalities.
p10
aVAnd the one that particularly bothered me in the burn department
p11
aVwas the process by which the nurses took the bandage off me.
p12
aVNow, you must have all taken a Band-Aid off at some point,
p13
aVand you must have wondered what's the right approach.
p14
aVDo you rip it off quickly \u2014 short duration but high intensity \u2014
p15
aVor do you take your Band-Aid off slowly \u2014
p16
aVyou take a long time, but each second is not as painful \u2014
p17
aVwhich one of those is the right approach?
p18
aa(lp19
VThe nurses in my department thought that the right approach
p20
aVwas the ripping one, so they would grab hold and they would rip,
p21
aVand they would grab hold and they would rip.
p22
aVAnd because I had 70 percent of my body burned, it would take about an hour.
p23
aVAnd as you can imagine,
p24
aVI hated that moment of ripping with incredible intensity.
p25
aVAnd I would try to reason with them and say,
p26
aV"Why don't we try something else?
p27
aVWhy don't we take it a little longer \u2014
p28
aVmaybe two hours instead of an hour \u2014 and have less of this intensity?"
p29
aVAnd the nurses told me two things.
p30
aVThey told me that they had the right model of the patient \u2014
p31
aVthat they knew what was the right thing to do to minimize my pain \u2014
p32
aVand they also told me that the word patient doesn't mean
p33
aVto make suggestions or to interfere or ...
p34
aVThis is not just in Hebrew, by the way.
p35
aVIt's in every language I've had experience with so far.
p36
aa(lp37
VAnd, you know, there's not much \u2014 there wasn't much I could do,
p38
aVand they kept on doing what they were doing.
p39
aVAnd about three years later, when I left the hospital,
p40
aVI started studying at the university.
p41
aVAnd one of the most interesting lessons I learned
p42
aVwas that there is an experimental method
p43
aVthat if you have a question you can create a replica of this question
p44
aVin some abstract way, and you can try to examine this question,
p45
aVmaybe learn something about the world.
p46
aa(lp47
VSo that's what I did.
p48
aVI was still interested
p49
aVin this question of how do you take bandages off burn patients.
p50
aVSo originally I didn't have much money,
p51
aVso I went to a hardware store and I bought a carpenter's vice.
p52
aVAnd I would bring people to the lab and I would put their finger in it,
p53
aVand I would crunch it a little bit.
p54
aa(lp55
V(Laughter)
p56
aa(lp57
VAnd I would crunch it for long periods and short periods,
p58
aVand pain that went up and pain that went down,
p59
aVand with breaks and without breaks \u2014 all kinds of versions of pain.
p60
aVAnd when I finished hurting people a little bit, I would ask them,
p61
aVso, how painful was this? Or, how painful was this?
p62
aVOr, if you had to choose between the last two,
p63
aVwhich one would you choose?
p64
aa(lp65
V(Laughter)
p66
aa(lp67
VI kept on doing this for a while.
p68
aa(lp69
V(Laughter)
